€LAY, x. (Sax. cleg; G. klet; TD. klet ; W.

elai; Dan. kleg, viscous, sticky.] 1. The name of certain substances which are mixtures of silex and alumin, sometimes with lime, magnesia, alkali and metallic oxyds. A species of earths which are firmly coherent, weighty, compact, and hard when dry, but stiff, viscid and ductile when moist, and smooth to the touch ; not readily diffusible in water, and when mix- ed, not readily subsiding in it. They con- tract by heat. Clays absorb water greed- ily, and become soft, but are so tenacious as to be molded into any shape, and hence they are the materials of bricks and vari- ous vessels, domestic and chimical.
